04493nam a22006855i 9781442674073DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161994onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426740737 a10.3138/97814426740732doi  a(DE-B1597)464410  a(OCoLC)979911421  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHT166b.G683 1994eb 7aPOL0020002bisacsh04a307.1/216/097162251 aGrant, Jill, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Drama of Democracy :bContention and Dispute in Community Planning /cJill Grant. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables, Maps, Photographs, and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart 1: All the World's a Stage -- tIntroduction: 'Everyone Loves a Mystery' -- t1. The Planning Drama -- t2. Stages, Actors, and Scripts -- tPart 2: Audience, Take Your Seats -- t3. Desperately Seeking Development -- t4. Planning Issues in Peninsular Halifax -- t5. Market Place Plaza -- t6. Mitchell Property -- tPart 3: The Reviews Are In -- t7. Staging Planning Activities -- t8. Command Performance -- t9. Scripts and Values -- tPart 4: Planning in a Democratic Society -- t10. Democracy in Myth and Practice -- t11. Planning Myths and Reality -- tAppendix: Glossary of Terms and Short Forms -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe drama of democracy seldom plays out as literally as it does in urban planning disputes. Yet these are complex dramas in which villains aren't clearly identified, protagonists are caught with ulterior motives, and fifth business runs rampant. In this book, Jill Grant aptly uses a dramaturgical metaphor to show how community planning offers illuminating episodes of the workings of democracy.Grant argues that planning provides a significant venue for the debate of major questions about how we govern ourselves. She illustrates her theory with two case studies of planning disputes in Halifax. By examining the language and actions of the citizens, planners, and politicians involved in these disputes, Grant explores underlying motives and concerns. Overall, this work has much to say about the nature of cultural obstacles that prevent greater democracy. The author concludes that while democracy is a valued cultural concept, its practice proves weak.Much of the work on urban planning takes a socio-economic perspective; the cultural implications of planning are still largely unexplored. By applying a cultural analysis to contemporary case studies, this book takes up the slack, thereby providing a timely addition to existing literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCity planningxCitizen participation. 0aCity planningzNova ScotiazHalifaxxCitizen participation. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267407340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442674073423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442674073.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK